stName>Clara</gtr:firstName><gtr:surname>Kulich</gtr:surname><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FF034962%2F1"><gtr:id>EC84C0CE-49AA-4BAA-BD3D-42830401FBEC</gtr:id><gtr:title>Gender Differences in Pay and Leadership Agency in Managerial Positions</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/F034962/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Clara Kulich,&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;ESRC post-doctoral fellow, does research on the reasons for the gender pay-gap, a highly topical issue which has recently been widely discussed in the British and European media. In the UK the pay gap in managerial positions is 26 per cent and has even increased in some sectors during the last year. In the EU it reaches 30 per cent and widens the higher up women climb the corporate ladder. Closing the pay gap is a crucial step in the endeavour to establish gender equality.&amp;nbsp;Kulichs' research contributes to these efforts by helping to understand the social psychological mechanisms underlying the gender pay-gap.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/p>

&lt;p>By conducting archival and experimental studies&amp;nbsp;it takes a closer look at how different contexts influence male and female directors' pay.&amp;nbsp;The research&amp;nbsp;analyses how company performance has an impact on male and female directors' performance-based pay in a distinct way.&amp;nbsp;It also explores the role of gender differences in money attitudes, negotiation behaviours and decision making on the gender pay-gap. Finally, an extensive examination of qualitative data about the stereotypes on the gender pay-gap displayed in reader comments on the web will reveal further valuable findings on public reactions to the discussion of gender inequalities.&lt;br />


